Context:

This dataset contains information about global university rankings published by the Center for World University Rankings (CWUR) from 2020 to 2025. It includes details such as each universitys world rank, national rank, education rank, employability rank, faculty rank, research rank, and overall score.

The data reflects the performance of universities from different countries based on education quality, research strength, and graduate employability.

Problem Statement:

The CWUR ranks universities worldwide based on education, research, and employability.Since the data is spread across different years, its hard to see changes and trends.This project collects and analyzes CWUR data from 20202025 & it aims to find trends, identify top-performing countries and universities, and understand which factors influence ranking performance.

Objectives::

The main objectives of this project are to:

  • Collect CWUR university ranking data from 2020 to 2025 using web scraping.
  • Combine data from all years into one clean and structured dataset.
  • Analyze and compare the rankings of universities and countries over time.
  • Identify the top-performing universities and countries each year.
  • Explore how different factors (education, employability, faculty, research) affect overall rankings.
  • Visualize trends and patterns in global higher education.
  • Generate insights that highlight changes in university performance worldwide.

Data Scraping

In[]:
async def fetch_cwur(year):
    # Dynamically construct the URL based on the year
    if year >= 2023: # For 2023, 2024, 2025 and onwards
        url = f"https://cwur.org/{year}.php"
    else: # For 2020, 2021, 2022 use YYYY-YY.php format
        # Example: 2020 becomes 2020-21
        end_year_suffix = str(year + 1)[-2:]
        url = f"https://cwur.org/{year}-{end_year_suffix}.php"

    session = AsyncHTMLSession()
    r = await session.get(url)
    await r.html.arender(sleep=2, timeout=30)  # async rendering

    # Find the table
    table = r.html.find('table#cwurTable', first=True)

    all_rows_for_year = []

    # Define the header row (needed by scrape_all_years logic)
    header_row = [
        "World Rank",
        "University",
        "Country",
        "National Rank",
        "Education Rank",
        "Employability Rank",
        "Faculty Rank",
        "Research Rank",
        "Score",
        "Year"
    ]

    # If table is not found, print a warning and return an empty list of data rows.
    if not table:
        print(f" Warning: Table 'cwurTable' not found for year {year} at {url}. Returning no data for this year.")
        # Return an empty list of data rows, the caller will handle the header separately.
        return [header_row] # Returning just header to maintain consistency for `scrape_all_years`

    # Iterate through table rows and extract data
    # Skip the first `tr` as it's typically the header in the HTML table.
    for row in table.find('tr')[1:]:
        cols = [c.text for c in row.find('td')]
        if cols:
            cols.append(str(year)) # Add the year as a string
            all_rows_for_year.append(cols)

    # Prepend the header row only if this fetch_cwur call is the one that's expected to provide the header.
    # However, the `scrape_all_years` function already handles adding the header once.
    # So, we just return the data rows, and `scrape_all_years` will manage the header from the first successful year's fetch.
    # To fit the current `scrape_all_years` logic (which expects data[0] to be header for first_year, and then data[1:] for subsequent), we always include the header here.
    all_rows_for_year.insert(0, header_row) # Insert header at the beginning

    return all_rows_for_year

Observation:

This fetch_cwur function scrapes university ranking data for a given year from the CWUR website. It builds the correct URL, loads the web page (including dynamic content), finds the ranking table, extracts all the data rows, adds the specified year to each row, and then returns the data along with a predefined header.

In[]:
all_years_data = []
years_to_scrape = range(2020, 2026) # Years from 2020 to 2025

async def scrape_all_years():
    global all_years_data # Declare all_years_data as global to modify it
    first_year = True

    for year in years_to_scrape:
        print(f"Scraping data for year: {year}")
        data = await fetch_cwur(year)

        if first_year:
            all_years_data.extend(data) # Include header for the first year
            first_year = False
        else:
            all_years_data.extend(data[1:]) # Exclude header for subsequent years
        print(f" Data for year {year} collected.")

    print(" All years data combined successfully.")

Observation:

  1. This code initializes an empty list to store all data.
  2. It defines the years to scrape (2020-2025) and then, in the scrape_all_years function, it loops through each year, calls fetch_cwur to get data, and combines all the results into a single list, ensuring headers are only included once.

Data Description

  • World Rank: The universitys global position.
  • University: Name of the institution.
  • Country: The country where the university is located.
  • National Rank: Universitys position within its own country.
  • Education Rank: Based on education quality and achievements.
  • Employability Rank: Based on alumni employment outcomes.
  • Faculty Rank: Based on faculty achievements and awards.
  • Research Rank: Based on research output and impact.
  • Score: Overall CWUR score based on all factors.
  • Year: The year of ranking data (20202025).

5. Handle Outliers (IQR Method for Score and 'National Rank')

In[39]:
def handle_outliers_iqr(df, column):
    Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # Cap values outside IQR range
    df[column] = np.where(df[column] < lower_bound, lower_bound,
                          np.where(df[column] > upper_bound, upper_bound, df[column]))
    return df

def top_countries_top100(df):
    df2 = df.copy()
    df2['World Rank'] = pd.to_numeric(df2['World Rank'], errors='coerce')
    top100 = df2[df2['World Rank'] <= 100]
    result = top100.groupby("Country")["University"].nunique().sort_values(ascending=False)
    return result

Q2: Universities that improved the most (2020 2025)

In[13]:
def top_improvers_2020_2025(df):
    df2 = df.copy()
    df2['World Rank'] = pd.to_numeric(df2['World Rank'])
    pivot = df2.pivot_table(index=['University', 'Country'], 
                            columns='Year', 
                            values='World Rank', 
                            aggfunc='first').reset_index()
    pivot = pivot.dropna(subset=[2020, 2025])
    pivot["Improvement"] = pivot[2020] - pivot[2025]  # positive = better
    return pivot.sort_values("Improvement", ascending=False).head(15)

def research_vs_world(df):
    df2 = df.dropna(subset=['World Rank', 'Research Rank'])
    corr, pval = spearmanr(df2['Research Rank'], df2['World Rank'])

def future_leader_countries(df):
    df2 = df.copy()
    df2['World Rank'] = pd.to_numeric(df2['World Rank'])
    
    pivot = df2.pivot_table(index=['University','Country'], 
                            columns='Year', values='World Rank',
                            aggfunc='first').reset_index()
    pivot = pivot.dropna(subset=[2020, 2025])
    pivot["Annual Improvement"] = (pivot[2020] - pivot[2025]) / 5
    result = pivot.groupby("Country")["Annual Improvement"].mean().sort_values(ascending=False)
    return result.head(15)
In[24]:
future_leaders = future_leader_countries(df_clean)

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) focused on understanding and refining the Center for World University Rankings (CWUR) dataset from 20202025. Univariate analysis revealed right-skewed rank variables and left-skewed score trends. Bivariate analysis showed strong relationships, especially between World Rank and Research Rank (0.97). Multivariate analysis showed that universities with strong research and education ranks consistently achieve higher overall performance. Overall, EDA provided meaningful insights into ranking patterns and prepared the dataset for visualization and deeper analysis.

The Data Visualization phase focused on uncovering patterns, trends, and relationships within the CWUR dataset from 20202025 using univariate, bivariate, and multivariate graphical analyses. Visualizations were applied to explore the distribution of ranks, scores, countries, and institutional performance metrics. Univariate plots revealed that world and national ranks were heavily right-skewed, indicating that most universities fall into mid-to-lower ranking positions, while only a small subset consistently appears at the top. Score distributions showed a narrow but stable range, reflecting the standardized scoring structure used by CWUR.

Bivariate visualizations highlighted a strong inverse pattern between World Rank and Score, where better-performing institutions consistently achieved higher scores. Scatterplots colored by year confirmed that this relationship remained stable across all six years, with only slight upward shifts as global ranking standards evolved. Brand-level (country-level) comparisons showed that countries such as the United States, the United Kingdom, and China repeatedly host institutions with superior scores and lower (better) world ranks. Boxplots further emphasized country-specific disparities, with top-performing nations showing tighter concentration of scores.

The correlation heatmap provided deeper insights by revealing meaningful relationships among numerical features. Score demonstrated strong negative correlation with World Rank and National Rank, reaffirming that higher-performing universities receive better rank positions. The heatmap also showed mild correlation between Year and World Rank, suggesting slight changes in ranking distributions over time. Pairplots supported these findings by visually confirming clustering behavior between high-score institutions and their corresponding rank positions.

Multivariate visualizations, including year-wise scatterplots and correlation matrices, showcased stable performance patterns among top universities, while also highlighting emerging competitiveness among institutions from rapidly developing countries. Overall, data visualizations offered clear, interpretable evidence that research performance, institutional quality, and country-level strength heavily influence global ranking outcomes. These visual analyses not only validated earlier EDA results but also provided a strong foundation for data mining and deeper analysis.

Bathini Shanmukha priya 2490778 - Report

The analysis of CWUR 20202025 focused on identifying the key factors influencing university performance and global rankings, employing a comprehensive data-mining approach that included regression, correlation, and clustering techniques. Five core research questions were advanced at the beginning: to predict university scores in accordance with the top globally ranked universities, to identify the most influential ranking factors, and to understand feature importance. Following cleaning and standardization-specifically converting ranking columns to a numeric form for World Rank, Research Rank, and Faculty Rank-exploratory data analysis was performed on the relationship between research quality, standards of education, employability, and faculty performance. This initial step is important in building an understanding of how different metrics relate to one another in establishing overall institutional success.

Further regression modeling was done to predict university scores based on features including Research Rank, Alumni Employment, and Education Quality. It was found that the most decisive predictors were Composite Score and then Research Rank, followed by Faculty Rank, while Employability and Education contributed relatively little. This was further reinforced by feature importance analysis; the model had a remarkably high generalization accuracy of approximately 99% on the test set, but this also hinted at overfitting that may imply redundancy among the predictor and target variables. The correlation analysis further showed a perfect inverse relation between Research Rank and World Rank, which pinpointed that research performance is indeed the linchpin to global recognition.

K-Means clustering was then applied to rank and performance metrics in order to cluster universities into distinct groups that separated research-intensive institutions from those strong in employability and teaching quality. From these analyses, ten key conclusions were identified about global diversification of academic excellence, the dominant role that research and faculty quality play in driving rankings performance, and the increasing presence of universities from Asia and the Middle East. In all, this research provided a data-driven view of how institutional attributes shape global rankings and formed a sound basis on which to base further visualization, predictive modeling, and strategic decision making in the field of higher education analytics.

In this data mining analysis, I used data from the Center for World University Rankings (CWUR) covering the years 2020 to 2025. I performed a data mining analysis to identify patterns in academic performance across the world. What specifically interested me was to know which regions have experienced the maximum improvement in ranking and to what extent these were attributed to the institutional factors of research quality, faculty performance, and standards of education. European universities continued to progress steadily, supported by stability and academic tradition. This trend, in conclusion, illustrates a changing global landscape of academic competitiveness.
